#!/bin/bash
# Script 1: System Identity Report
# Author: Rasika Jain | Course: Open Source Software

# -------- Variables --------
STUDENT_NAME="Rasika Jain"
SOFTWARE_CHOICE="Git"

# -------- System Information --------
KERNEL=$(uname -r)                          # Get kernel version
USER_NAME=$(whoami)                         # Get current user
HOME_DIR=$HOME                              # Get home directory
UPTIME=$(uptime -p)                         # Get system uptime
DATE_TIME=$(date)                           # Get current date and time

# Get Linux distribution name from system file
DISTRO=$(grep PRETTY_NAME /etc/os-release | cut -d= -f2 | tr -d '"')

# -------- Display Output --------
echo "======================================"
echo " Open Source Audit — $STUDENT_NAME"
echo "======================================"

echo "Chosen Software  -> $SOFTWARE_CHOICE"
echo "Linux Distro     -> $DISTRO"
echo "Kernel Version   -> $KERNEL"
echo "Current User     -> $USER_NAME"
echo "Home Directory   -> $HOME_DIR"
echo "System Uptime    -> $UPTIME"
echo "Current DateTime -> $DATE_TIME"

# -------- License Information --------
echo "--------------------------------------"
echo "This system follows open-source concepts"
echo "and is generally distributed under GNU GPL license."
echo "This output is generated as part of my project work."
echo "--------------------------------------"

This script displays important system information in a structured format. It shows details like Linux distribution name, kernel version, logged-in user, home directory, uptime, and current date and time.
The script uses variables to store values and command substitution $( ) to execute Linux commands such as uname, whoami, and uptime. It also reads system details from /etc/os-release to get the distribution name. The echo command is used for displaying output in a formatted way.
Through this script, I understood how to use basic shell scripting concepts like variables, command substitution, and formatted output. I also got practical experience working with system-level commands in Linux.
Script 2 — FOSS Package Inspector
